Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamm told him that he was dealing with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for leave for health reasons, saying he had some health problems.
This year, he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes in the university’s employment policy meant that the PhD, for which Lamb had worked so hard, would not be a guarantee for him of an automatic path to employment as an assistant professor.
University President William LaForge said he knew nothing about a conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but "of course there was something in Mr. Lamb's imagination."
These are questions that Lamb can no longer answer.
After escaping from the campus, police later found Lamb's trace as he returned to Mississippi from Arkansas.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb killed himself with a .38 caliber gun in the backyard of a house about a mile south of his parent’s home on the outskirts of Greenville, Mississippi, Washington County Coroner Methel Johnson said.
His car was still in the entrance.
It wasn’t immediately clear why Lamb went to that house, but Johnson said she believes he knew the people who lived there.
Lamb grew up in the area.
Lamb began his work at the University in 2009, which has 3,500 students in a city of about 12,000 inhabitants and taught geography and pedagogy.
He graduated in pedagogics in the spring.
One of Lamb’s longtime friends described him as intelligent, charismatic and funny.
