People who smoke have a higher risk of losing their teeth.
Those who smoke harm not only the lungs, but also the teeth - this is suggested by a long-term Potsdam study.
The good news is that withdrawal reduces the risk rapidly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evidenced by a long-term study by an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers had a 2.5 to 3.6 times higher risk of premature tooth loss.
The researchers followed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are caries and inflammation of the gums, emphasizes the DIfE.
Smoking is a risk factor for this periodontitis, the authors emphasize.
The link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more common gum inflammation among smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers wrote in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years before the risk drops back to the level of non-smokers, first author Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham explained.
One has to convince people to become non-smokers, said study leader Heiner Boeing of DIfE: "Smoking shortens life."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health up to old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE.
Previous research has shown that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
