EU Commission proposes new court for TTIP dispute
To escalate the dispute over the planned transatlantic free trade agreement TTIP, the European Commission has proposed a comprehensive reform of the current arbitration system.
The contested private arbitration bodies for disputes between corporations and states are therefore to be replaced by a more transparent system, which in its functioning corresponds to much more traditional courts.
“We want to establish a system that citizens trust,” said EU Commissioner Cecilia Malmström.
Sweden intends to include the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the United States.
The German government announced its support.
TTIP will create the world’s largest free trade zone with 800 million people.
The plans to reform the current arbitration proceedings specifically provide that EU countries and the U.S. jointly select independent judges for a new investment court.
They should come in equal proportions from the EU, the United States and third countries.
For the first time, a second instance is also planned.
It would allow to appeal against judgments.
So far, the parties to the proceedings agreed on arbitrators, there was no possibility of appeal against their judgments.
The discussion over the past months has made it clear that citizens did not trust the old ISDS system in matters of fairness and justice, Malmström commented.
In the long run, it wants to work towards an International Investment Court.
In this case, disputes between Chinese companies and EU countries could also be resolved.
The Investor-State Arbitration (ISDS), which is mostly demanded by large corporations, is considered to be one of the main reasons for the strong opposition in Europe to TTIP.
Traditional arbitration courts are criticized by opponents as a kind of parallel justice through which companies can claim damages at the expense of taxpayers, override national laws, or enforce a reduction in consumer and environmental standards.
In initial opinions, anti-TTIP organizations such as Campact called the proposals of the EU Commission inadequate.
They were criticized in particular for not applying to the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada (CETA).
German Economy Secretary Matthias Machnig (SPD) described the plans as great progress.
The Commission takes into account the key points drawn up by German Economy Minister Sigmar Gabriel in the spring with other EU trade ministers.
The old system of private arbitration courts is out of the table.
The French government also welcomed the plans of Malmström.
The European business association BusinessEurope warned against limiting the lawsuits opportunities of the business by too many new rules.
Especially small and medium-sized could be disadvantaged by this.
When the negotiations on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) can be concluded remained unclear on Wednesday.
The negotiations have been ongoing since mid-2013.
The issue of investor protection has not yet been discussed with the United States.
Initially, a framework for the agreement should be in place by the end of this year.
This date is no longer sustainable.
