Jeremy Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Hour
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn’s debut at the Prime Minister’s Question Hour is expected with excitement
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn is scheduled to make his debut at the Prime Minister’s Question Hour and meet for the first time with David Cameron.
Mr. Corbyn will stand up to ask the first of his six prearranged questions shortly after lunch, with his performance likely to be checked closely by the media and Labour MPs.
He called for "less theatre and more facts" at this weekly event.
He also said he could skip some sessions to leave them to colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test for Mr Corbyn’s leadership, as it comes after his appointment as a member of the Shadow Cabinet and after his speech at the TUC Annual Meeting on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader’s decision to remain silent on Tuesday while singing the national anthem at a commemoration ceremony commemorating the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has provoked criticism from a number of Tory MPs and is at the center of several front-page stories in newspapers.
Mr. Corbyn’s decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr. Corbyn said he had "standed in respectful silence" and he recognized the "heroism of the Royal Air Force in the air battle for England."
But a member of Mr Corbyn’s shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told the BBC’s Two Newsnight program that he had advised the Labour leader to sing the national anthem “regardless” of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve in Mr Corbyn’s top team, citing differences in business, defense and foreign policy, while less than a sixth of the Parliamentary Party originally supported him as a leader.
BBC Political Correspondent Robin Brant says political differences are also “accumulating” within Labour, following Mr. Corbyn’s statements about the position on the European Union and the limitation of profits.
Mr. Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour is proposing amendments to remove the whole idea of a limitation overall.
Hours later, Mr. Smith, the Shadow Labour and Pension Minister, said the party was “very clear” that it was only against the government’s plans to lower the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr. Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron over the dispatch box in parliament over the past decade, since he has been the leader of the Tory.
The Labour leader, who promised a different policy approach, says he has "crowd-sourced" ideas for questions to Mr. Cameron and he has been given more than 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP has said that the prime minister’s question hour is too confrontational, and that he will refrain from both “strike skill” and fighting with hiccups and has instead set out to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr. Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the Shadow Economy Minister, will represent him if he does not attend - for example, if Mr. Cameron is traveling abroad.
He also introduced the idea that other colleagues occasionally take the word, and that he addressed John Bercow, the House spokesman, to discuss the issue.
When he became leader in 2005, Mr. Cameron said he wanted to move away from politics in the style of a "Kasperle Theatre", often associated with the prime minister's question hour.
Since it was first broadcast on television in 1990, the question hour with the prime minister was seen as the main barometer of a leader’s judgment and his leadership in the House of Commons and his position among his parliamentary counterparts, although critics have argued it has become a caricature and needs far-reaching reforms.
