Metcash Launches Ground Stability Campaign to Combat Aldi Invasion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi rise in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-stability campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as through events such as the Adelaide Show.
IGA dealers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands like Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo, who distributes samples in IGA stores, and store owners who sell endorsed tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, as the wholesaler for food, alcohol and equipment carries out its annual investor strategy day.
Much is at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA store trades and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the Eastern States.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the Eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will take away about five percent of the food market in these two states 12 months after opening its first markets, taking away sales from all existing players, but mostly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and food business and in the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed cost base could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr. Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market shares in the Eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey conducted by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash’s food and food sales will drop by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and will reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, top fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash refused to publicly respond to Mr. Douglass’s comments.
But it is assumed that a member of the Metcash board contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has dropped from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenues from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies approximately 1,200 IGA retailers, have dropped by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while simultaneously putting pressure on revenue and margins.
The wholesaler, however, resists and invests more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, improving IGA retailers in improving their stores by growing fresh food faster and delivering a better selection of private-label foods.
Metcash chief executive Ian Morrice says price adjustments and store repair programs will add to Elan and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by Australian Tennis Association President Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves more praise than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral injuries" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves more praise than criticism for his own behavior, according to the president of the Australian Tennis Federation Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came to light by Kyrgios's infamous confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fierce qualifying game in Cincinnati shortly thereafter, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison shouting out, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should beating the child."
While he was last seen crushing a tennis pit after a crash disrupted a potential US Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was firmly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the single behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Britain.
“One thing I’m pretty upset about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi was a bit involved in the fight,” Healy said.
He broke a beat when he lost because of a cramp at the US Open, but he’s not the first player to break a beat with himself out of frustration, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the US Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he’s been treated a bit too severely.
He’s a very mature 19-year-old, he’s working very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he’s never had a problem with the other players before, he’s respected in dressing, he’s training hard, he’s in good shape, he’s a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged by his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important preliminary decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the “joint decision” as the right one for all, but he assures the Canberra man to return to the team as a long-term fixed part.”
“First, we want the team to be fully focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I think Nick has made the rise very quickly, as people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions.
