This will happen if the Fed raises interest rates
An increase in interest rates will come, and the rise will swing, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we do not know is how long this all will last and how long it will last.
In particular, history provides little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial investments react.
That’s why representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when it starts raising interest rates, but rather on the time needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that all the excitement over an interest rate hike may have been exaggerated.
“The Fed’s first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘cheap money’,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still at levels too low to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no effects.
Here is a look based on historical trends on how some sectors of the economy could react:
As the market has seen over the past month, anticipating interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase comes, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There appears to be a tendency that asset revenues are slashing 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after Fed interest rate increases.
More specifically, the market is mostly on the uptrend over the past 35 years — about 14 percent — on the path to interest rate increases, fairly flat in the 250 days afterwards (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six cycles of 14.4 percent according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, at Barron’s.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on stocks tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the yield begins to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
Very remarkable here is that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point when the Fed raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, in the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, the nominal GDP was only twice below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect it to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rate increases in such a fragile economic setting could be risky and raise the question "whether it will be different this time," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been focusing on a Fed interest rate hike all year round, and all eyes have been on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week that ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, the futures trade only gives a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all growth cycles from 1950 to the present day have taken place in a super-cycle with increasing GDP momentum and shadowed pre-recession heights very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate rise, and the pattern is pretty similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic course.
In bonds, yields appear to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields drop immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will cause returns between longer and shorter bonds to come closer together and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we’re still cautious to expect higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adjusted to Fed’s strategic expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flat, credit margins have expanded and volatility has risen – all features of the market as the Fed tightenes its strategy.
Overall, companies that operate most of their business in the U.S. will benefit from rising interest rates and increasing the attractiveness of local products.
High-debted multinationals will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive on the global market, as is the financing of their debt.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate hike,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a customer report.
Companies with a strong balance sheet surpassed companies with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their stocks also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt becomes a big problem.
Companies with a high percentage of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside the pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers might see profits from higher returns, even though experts differ on how quickly that will happen.
