A government-funded agency’s claims that e-cigarettes are less harmful than smoking came from a meeting of 12 people, some with links to the tobacco industry, researchers said.
Experts writing in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) joined the Lancet by criticizing the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE released the “Principle Report” last month, describing it as a “comprehensive review of evidence.”
However, some researchers have questioned the resilience of the data and pointed to the links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
A editorial article in the medical journal Lancet last month attacked the “extremely windy foundation” on which PHE founded its most important conclusion.
Two other researchers write in BMJ and have asked if the claims are “built on stone or sand.”
Martin McKee, Professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: “A fundamental principle of public health is that strategies should be based on evidence of effectiveness.”
They said the public expects PHE’s claim that “the current best estimate is that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than smoking” to be based on a detailed review of evidence and modeling.
In fact, this statement comes from a single meeting of 12 people who were summoned to develop a model for Multi-Criteria Decision Analysis (MCDA) to synthesize their opinions about the harm of different nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting were summarized in a research report.
McKee and Capewell said one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEOs are said to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco (BAT) for an independent study.
He also signed BAT’s public health references in a sustainability report, they said.
One of the 12 participants at the meeting stated that he was receiving funding from an e-cigarette manufacturer, but not the funding he allegedly received previously from tobacco company Philip Morris International, they added.
The reasons for selecting panel members are not provided, but these include several well-known e-cigarette champions, some of whom also indicate industry funding in the paper.
Some other participants in this session are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The tobacco management of PHE also participated in the meeting.
The group’s research work “confirms significantly” that there is a lack of “hard evidence for the damage of most products to most criteria,” McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these connections or restrictions are discussed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE’s claims that “there is no evidence so far that e-cigarettes serve as a way to smoke for children or non-smokers” were premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of health and well-being at PHE, said that BMJ’s claims have been responded earlier.
He said, “E-cigarettes are much less harmful than smoking.”
One in two lifelong smokers dies from their addiction.
All evidence suggests that the health risks of e-cigarettes are low compared to that, but that we continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has the clear duty to inform the public about what the evidence proves and what it does not, especially when there is so much public confusion about the relative hazards compared to tobacco.
Nearly 80,000 people die each year from a smoking-related disease, and smoking costs the National Health System £2 billion a year.
By clearly presenting current evidence that e-cigarettes are not without risk, but represent only a fraction of the harm caused by smoking, we are fulfilling our national competence.
