At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide whether it’s time to raise the key interest rates for the first time in a decade.
Threatening over them at one end of the decorated, two-story meeting room is a wall picture of the United States.
The card is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation above all other things.
The central bank has a double mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-Factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict.It will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start to be detached from the unprecedented incentive by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows that it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could make the already cautious Fed representatives afraid to boost this volatility by raising federal bond interest rates – even if only by a quarter percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the most important thing they’re watching first,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for a pretext not to raise interest rates, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to keep waiting,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself makes the financial market uncertain.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg have predicted an interest rate rise this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of a rise.
This suggests a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate unless the strategists soften the blow by promising that another rise is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 228.89 points or 1.4 percent to 16.599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates at this point," he said.
If she does, "she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argued that an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove the uncertainty about when the Fed would trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in the rate this year despite the complaints of liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And while inflation was consistently below the central bank’s annual 2% target, the Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shaken at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell more than 16% below its peak in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market has somewhat recovered this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the high of May.
For the Fed representatives, market turbulence affects the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
"If the events in the financial markets and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would have pulled the tricks in this session," said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Central Bank.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to get the effects better under control.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there are almost no reliable data describing developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere indication by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “constrain” its monetary expansion caused confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA., noted this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that appear to be unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, who advocates an interest rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia caused the Fed to lower its core interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions "despite limited noticeable effects on U.S. growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed reversed these cuts.
The Fed should only put aspects of financial stability first during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
Recent turbulences are not coming close to that level, he said.
“She doesn’t want to get into the situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets get upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should go ahead of time.
