Robot cars: Government wants to play a pioneering role for Germany
Germany, according to the will of the federal government, should be a technological pioneer in changing the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet adopted a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which, among other things, provides for investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the IAA on Wednesday of a “new era of mobility”.
Automated and connected driving will increase traffic safety and reduce congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The Ministry of Transportation’s strategy paper emphasizes, among other things, the importance of the expansion of mobile broadband and a rapid transition to digital audio.
For the testing of new technology, a test track is currently being created on Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order for the driver "not to be charged with additional liability risks", the federal government wants to review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments.
Germany, for example, is committed to raising the maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 km/h.
The federal government also wants to push for a change to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car increasingly takes the lead, the driver becomes more and more the passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are not expected until far beyond 2020.
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the site in Germany is estimated by the authors of the study to be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
“The digital networking of the car can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road traffic,” said Sören Bartol, the SPD’s transport politician.
However, the issue of liability in case of accidents and the safety of driver’s personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still view self-driving cars with skepticism – much more than the French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the test organization Dekra, presented at the AA on Wednesday, concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect it only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect to have autonomous cars by 2025, compared to 33 percent in the U.S.
German drivers are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to give up control during the entire ride on all roads.
On the highway this could be imagined in the flowing traffic 15 percent, in the congestion 45 percent.
Approximately one in four would not leave control of the car under any circumstances.
