Xi urges wider opening of the economy to the world
The economy needs to open more widely to the outside to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group commissioned to guide the reform on Tuesday.
"China should strive to attract foreign investment and know-how and improve strategies for business startups," he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group on Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Encouraging new foundations and pushing forward reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Governing Group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list on regulating market access, easing border control policies, promoting state-owned enterprises (SOE), incorporating private capital, and overhauling the resident notification system.
According to the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually being tested and improved through test programs.
The initiative is important because it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a rule of law business environment and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls over the powers delegated to companies and ensure that companies decide how to conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open government-controlled sectors, further areas will be opened for private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide better services to them," the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right to guarantee lawyers to carry out their activities and to employ professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at a hearing.
