EU plans to double the level of mercury in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby giving consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve poison.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a relevant EU work paper, sharply criticized the plans: “The risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are being passed on with full emphasis to pregnant women and young children,” said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values of the nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain such as sharks or swordfish are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily loaded with mercury that on the basis of the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches are not allowed to be sold.
If the limit values were doubled, only 14.5 percent would remain out of sale.
In exchange for this easing, the EU plans to tighten the limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller landfish, such as carp, are usually loaded so low that they meet the planned maximum levels already today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perverse distraction maneuver that only helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which is heavily enriched throughout the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that “already small amounts, especially in unborn children, can cause damage to the nervous system.”
However, the Federal Ministry of Environment declares on its homepage that a “health hazard to the general population” is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the combustion of coal.
German coal-fired power plants are emitting more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written report from the Federal Ministry of Environment to the Greens-Bundestags member Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish such as in the Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube was "permanently and widespreadly exceeded," the "Spiegel" quoted in the paper in March.
Last year, EU-wide warnings about mercury in fish were already among the most commonly health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
